    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MuTA23">
<l>virumpiviṇ maṇṇaḷanta vañciṟaiya vaṇṭār</l>
<l>curumpu tuḷaiyiṟceṉ ṟūta – varumpum</l>
<l>puṉantuḻāy mālaiyāṉ poṉṉaṅ kaḻaṟkē</l>
<l>maṉantuḻāy mālāy varum</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>[My] mind, being stirred up into confusion<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">mālāy has to be analysed as an early occurrence of the modern type of adverb formation, occasionally already found also in the Kīḻkkaṇakku with -ā (verbal root) or -āka (infinitive) as a suffix, such as puṟamāka, “outside” in Tiṇaimālai Nūṟṟaimpatu 117.3.</note>, comes</l>
<l>to the [feet with] golden anklets of him with a tulsi garland from the fields,</l>
<l>that bud for bees to go into [the flower] tubes [and] fill themselves up,</l>
<l>while others<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The two words for the two different kinds of bees are vaṇṭu and curumpu.</note> with pretty wings that measured heaven [and] earth<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here the trivikrama standard motif of measuring heaven and earth is playfully attributed to the bees, in an extension of the old Akam topos of bees being connoisseurs of all the flowers that exist.</note> hum desirously.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
